There is no greater act of patriotism than serving your country in the armed forces. In this spirit, tonight I re-introduced my ENLIST Act to allow young undocumented immigrants brought here by their parents the ability to earn legal status in the country they consider to be home. Immigrants have served honorably in our armed forces for decades, and this would be a positive step forward for our nation as we seek a collective solution to immigration reform. More: http://bit.ly/2ixc1Os

#MorningMailbag: Over the last few months, I've been hearing a lot of your concerns about executive authority and overreach. As your representative, it's my responsibility to protect and defend the U.S. Constitution, which includes critical checks and balances that were incorporated with consideration for the separation of powers. The legislative branch acts as an important check on the power of the executive, and I will do everything in my power to ensure that the Central Valley's interests are not only heard, but also protected. I answer to you - the people - and no one else.

Join me in welcoming retired Staff Sgt. Peter Butler as he joins my team as a Wounded Warrior Fellow! Pete, who counts a Bronze Star and a Purple Heart amongst his many accolades, will serve as a liaison to veterans and veteran groups in CA-10. Glad and honored to have you on board, Pete!

Seeking solutions for the Valley's water issues is a top priority for me during the 115th Congress. Today I re-introduced my "New WATER Act" to authorize a pilot program to increase water infrastructure development, and yesterday I sent a letter to the U.S. Bureau of Reclamation, U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service and National Marine Fisheries Service requesting that they increase pumping to rates to continue capturing the storm water runoff entering the Delta from the recent rains. Read on to learn more.

I understand that Californians are concerned about a repeal of the Affordable Care Act that does not provide an adequate replacement. There are several provisions that I support and will fight to keep, like ensuring care for those with pre-existing conditions and allowing children up to age 26 to remain on their parents' plans. But overall, the ACA is a hastily-written, non-sustainable healthcare policy. We must do better.

I have joined my colleague U.S. Rep. Katherine Clark in reintroducing the Pet and Women Safety (PAWS) Act - a bicameral, bipartisan bill to assist domestic violence survivors and their pets. Multiple studies have shown that domestic abusers often seek to manipulate or intimidate their victims by threatening or harming their pets, yet only 3% of domestic violence shelters across the country accept pets. The result is that victims of domestic violence are held captive emotionally while their beloved pets are used as pawns to prolong an abusive relationship. We must make it possible for women to break free knowing that their pets will be able to move with them wherever they go. I applaud those shelters and programs that have already worked to accommodate pets, and I will continue pushing with my colleagues for a nationwide standard.

In this week's #MorningMailbag, I discuss the ENLIST Act, a bill I recently re-introduced. The ENLIST Act would allow otherwise qualified undocumented immigrants, brought here through no fault of their own, to earn legal status through military service. As someone who served alongside immigrants, I believe that those who protect our shores and defend the values that make us proud to call America the land of the free and home of the brave deserve an earned pathway to citizenship.

Appreciate Mayor O’Brien inviting me to speak at the Riverbank State of the City. The uncertainty surrounding the transfer of the Riverbank Ammunition Depot from the Department of the Army has gone on for way too long. My staff and I have engaged on this issue, and next week I will be meeting with the acting Undersecretary of the Army and Mayor O’Brien to finalize the transfer of the property, as promised. Between the leases on the depot itself and the potential for an intermodal yard with critical rail access for our Valley ag industry, this will be an economic boon for our community. I am committed to ensuring promises made by the Department of the Army are kept.

Thousands of veterans who laid their lives on the line for our country are waiting for their claims to be processed, and it's a disgrace the VA is putting those same lives at risk by refusing to cut through red tape and bureaucratic backlogs. Today, I surprised Roy Haury, a Korean War veteran from Patterson out in DC with the Central Valley Honor Flight, by presenting him with the Purple Heart of his brother, Marvin, who was killed in World War II. Roy's family had thought the Purple Heart was lost until it was discovered buried in a trunk. It was truly an honor to join the Valley's veterans as they visited the memorials built in their honor and to thank Roy and his brother for their sacrifices for our freedom.

Today I had the great honor of presenting Marvin R. Haury’s Purple Heart to his younger brother, Korean War Marine Veteran Roy Haury. Marvin Haury was in the Army during WWII and died Dec. 7, 1944 in Lindern, Germany in the ramp up to the Battle of the Bulge. I am forever grateful to our nation’s veterans for their sacrifices. From the bottom of my heart, thank you.

#MorningMailbag: I've been reading letters and emails about healthcare reform and want to reassure you that I'm fighting to expand access in the Central Valley. I'm working on ensuring equitable coverage that will help underserved areas like ours attract and retain both primary care providers and specialists to serve the growing Medi-Cal community. We also need to put an end to the doctor shortage in the Valley by expanding medical residency programs to incentivize more physicians to serve and hopefully remain in high-Medicaid areas. Today I voted with my colleagues in the U.S. House of Representatives to pass the American Health Care Act. As amended, I believe the final bill is a good first step toward putting control over personal healthcare choices back into the hands of individuals, stabilizing America's healthcare system, and ultimately bringing costs down. But we still have work to do to ensure that the Valley's issues with physician access are addressed. The House is already in the process of passing additional legislation to further strengthen the American healthcare system, such as Rep. Martha McSally's bill that ensures Members of Congress and their staff are treated the same way as everyone else under the AHCA, and I will also be introducing legislation in the coming weeks to address the Valley's unique healthcare needs.  My full statement as well as additional information on the AHCA are posted on the Healthcare page on my website if you want to learn more. Please continue contacting my office with your questions and comments as we move forward.

Yesterday, I was proud to join with all of my colleagues in the House to unanimously pass the "Forever GI Bill," which amends current law providing educational assistance to servicemembers and veterans. The legislation sent to the Senate last night removes the 15-year cap on utilizing the benefits offered to veterans retired from active-duty service and expands benefits for reservists, Purple Heart recipients and dependents. There are millions of brave men and women who have stepped up to defend our country, and this is a critical step towards assimilating them back into civilian life and providing them with resources and opportunities to succeed.

Today is National Hire A Veteran Day and as chairman of the Congressional Veterans Jobs Caucus, I'm committed to working on solutions with my colleagues on both sides of the aisle and across the Capitol that will improve the transition from military to civilian life for our veterans and their families. I'm honored to count three veterans as team members on my staff and am inspired by many others across the nation that have given our vets jobs.

I’ve been seeing and hearing about appointments being required to visit my Modesto office – which is completely false. While appointments are helpful to ensure staff is available, they are not (nor have they ever been) required; constituents are allowed to stop by without an appointment. Unfortunately, a recent protest caused so much disruption to other tenants and their customers – with over 100 deflated balloons among the litter left scattered throughout the property – that the landlord has requested no further activities take place on premises that disturb the quiet enjoyment of other building tenants, which is within their rights as the property owner. I support constituents’ right to peaceable assembly and protest, but out of respect to our landlord and neighbors, activity of this nature must take place on the public right of way only. If you would like to request a meeting, please visit my website → https://denham.house.gov/contact/meeting-request.htm

My statement on the president's DACA announcement today: "We should be dedicating our resources to securing our borders and deporting the violent criminals preying on our communities, not going after individuals who were brought to America as children through no fault of their own. The government asked these young men and women to come out of the shadows, and they have passed background checks, opened bank accounts, gotten jobs, enrolled in our universities -- all positive contributions to our society and our economy. To target them now is wrong. We have several widely-supported immigration reform bills already introduced this Congress, in both the House and Senate, that would address a path forward for DACA recipients. We must act immediately to pass these if we're to meet the president's six-month deadline."
In this week's #MorningMailbag I address your concerns about the President's announcement on #DACA and share what I'm doing on immigration reform in America.

Today we are celebrating the 167th anniversary of California’s admission into the Union as the thirty-first state. California was ceded to the United States by Mexico as part of the Compromise of 1850 at the end of the Mexican-American War at a time when slavery was an issue of huge contention in American politics. We were admitted to the Union as a free state following heated debate over the issue here in Congress. Happy birthday California!

Today I issued the following statement in observance of the September 11, 2001 terrorist attacks on our nation: “It’s been 16 years since terrorists struck a cowardly blow to our nation. As we commemorate this somber day and honor the nearly 3,000 American lives lost, we must remember that freedom, safety and national security are American priorities that must be defended at all costs. Thank you to our brave first responders and military servicemembers who protect us both here and abroad each day. God bless you all, and God bless the United States of America.”

The House voted yesterday to include an amendment to the 2018 spending bill that I authored to prevent homeless youth and young mothers from seeing a lapse in service from their Runaway Youth Programs and Maternity Group Homes. This amendment does not increase funding for the program, but it does prevent centers from facing a gap in grant eligibility. These centers are critical to our community, as they provide temporary shelter, counseling and transitional services to homeless, pregnant, and parenting youth to promote long-term economic independence to ensure their well-being. Watch my full remarks on the House floor.

Last night the Community Health and Medical Professionals Improve Our Nation (CHAMPION) Act of 2017 was introduced in the House, with many of the provisions I have been pushing to improve healthcare in the Valley. The bill would more than double funding for residencies to $126.5 million and expand the Teaching Health Center Graduate Medical Education (THCGME) programs, like we have in the Valley Consortium for Medical Education in Modesto. This is a big deal for communities like ours facing a doctor shortage, since doctors tend to practice where they complete residency. Rep. Kevin McCarthy and others in House leadership are supportive of the efforts, and I'm hopeful that we'll see movement on it soon. For more information about the bill and the THCGME program, visit my website and read the press release. → http://bit.ly/2fK3ncT

The House passed the FY 2018 budget this week, which means we can finally turn our attention to fixing America's broken tax code. Our tax code hasn't been revised since 1986. It's time to make it work for America again. In this #MorningMailbag, I reply to a letter from Lynette from Modesto and discuss how I am working to protect the Central Valley's interests as we reform the tax code.

A #TVT thank you to former Navy Petty Officer 2nd Class Walt Butler who served as a Navy reservist in the Vietnam War and is considered a ‘Blue Water’ Veteran. While running transports from the carrier to the Vietnam shore, Butler was exposed to Agent Orange but has struggled to receive related care from the V.A. since he was technically serving in coastal waters only. I have co-sponsored a bill to help vets like Walt receive the care they deserve. Thank you, Walt, for your service.

The House must continue its work to reform and reauthorize the FAA and pass the 21st Century AIRR Act. After spending over $7 billion, the FAA still uses outdated radar technology and paper strips for air traffic control. The reforms in this bill would provide more on-time departures and arrivals and fewer cancelled flights. #21AIRRact #FAAreform

Tune in here to watch a Facebook Live of the event at 3:30 EDT / 12:30 PDT! An early #TVT thank you to the veterans who have shared their stories with me and my staff. Yesterday I presented 12 interviews with Central Valley veterans to the The Library of Congress. Former Navy Petty Officer Second Class Lyle Ducheneaux was among them. Thank you to Lyle for your service and for taking the time to share your incredible story. #TVT

People in the Valley are taxed too much. It’s time we put in place a simpler, fairer tax plan – one that will not only cut taxes and put money in people’s pockets, but also will allow our small businesses to grow and hire more people. https://fairandsimple.gop/

With Veterans Day on the horizon, I want to say thank you to World War II Veteran John Fitisoff, a former Able Body Seaman who served in the Pacific Theater and was involved in the invasion of Okinawa. Thank you to John for sharing his story with my office! Watch here as he recounts seeing Japanese planes shot down by his convoy in Okinawa. #TVT

Over the past few months I have gathered interviews with Central Valley veterans to share with the Library of Congress as part of their #VeteransHistoryProject. Through this journey, several folks asked if I would share my story as well, so I recently sat down with my Wounded Warrior Fellow Pete Butler to do just that. I joined the United States Air Force in 1984 at the age of 17, with the blessing of my wonderful mother, who had to sign for me at that age. Through my service, I developed my values and came to better understand and respect our constitution. I strive to bring my experiences to the table in Congress, making veterans issues a priority and fighting for others who have fought to protect our nation. While we have made progress toward better fulfilling our nation’s promises to our veterans, our work is far from finished. I will keep fighting for the men and women who have so selflessly worn the cloth of this nation. Thank you to our veterans and God Bless America.

Veterans Day is a time to honor and thank those who dedicated their lives to protecting our nation. As a veteran myself, I understand the sacrifice involved in joining the military and fighting for this great nation. That is why I continue to fight here in Congress to improve care and opportunities for veterans and to recognize and thank our Central Valley veterans for their service with my #TVT initiative. On this Veterans Day, please join me in thanking all who have served our country.

Today I sent a letter signed by 78 of my colleagues and supported by the National Network for Youth to the House Committee on Appropriations requesting a fix for expiring Transition Living Program (TLP) and Maternity Group Home (MGH) grants. Homelessness is a major issue we face in the Central Valley, and a loss of services that have proven successful would be a serious setback for our community and ultimately increase the homeless youth population. Shelters like the Center for Human Services in Modesto make a big difference, and we cannot afford to see them shut down because of a failure of Congress to act. Click through to read more.

Every year, the federal government spends billions of dollars rebuilding the same structures in the same places with little consideration of the next disaster. It’s time to take action to save lives and taxpayer money by thinking ahead when we build our communities, instead of typical reactionary government policies. So I've introduced the SMART Rebuilding Act, aimed at lowering the cost of natural disasters by helping states and communities plan ahead and rebuild smarter. More: https://denham.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=2146

Seventy-six years ago, we were attacked at Pearl Harbor. While we recognize the battle that propelled the United States into World War II, we must also remember the selfless acts of our men and women in uniform as well as the many civilians that rescued survivors from the Pacific waters and the doctors, nurses and police officers who responded in the face of uncertain danger. Together they saved American lives. It is important we continue to recognize them for their call to duty and remember those that paid the ultimate price. On this Thank-a-Vet Thursday, I want to pay special tribute to the Greatest Generation.

Congress has delivered on our promise to lower taxes for the middle class by reducing rates while preserving the credits and deductions that matter most to the people I represent – like the now-doubled Child Tax Credit. The lowering of marginal tax rates means Americans will receive more money in their paychecks immediately, and at minimum, the first $12,000 to $24,000 of their paychecks will be tax-free. This is a win for the Valley and for everyone who will see an increase in their paychecks in 2018. But the biggest issue in the Valley has always been jobs. This bill will expand exports on the many things we grow in our community, which will allow our local agricultural businesses to be more globally competitive and hire more of our neighbors. For more info, see my full release here: https://denham.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=2186

Yesterday, Congress officially passed the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act to provide much-needed tax relief for individuals and families and bring jobs back into our communities. Families will now be able to deduct $24,000 from their tax liability under the new Standard Deduction – an increase of about $12,000. All considered, the average family of four will save a total of about $1,500. In this week’s Morning Mailbag, I address this and some of your other top questions about the bill:

This emergency wildfire aid bill is the third disaster recovery bill, now totaling almost $133 billion in resources passed in response to catastrophic wildfires and hurricanes in 2017, and the second influx of funding specific to California recovery totaling over $5 billion in aid. Until now, federal resources were spent rebuilding the same structures in the same disaster-prone places. My policies will provide resources and incentives for communities to plan for the next event by mitigating future damages to save lives and taxpayer dollars. These are disaster prevention reforms that represent a wise investment. See my full release here: https://denham.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=2192
